float shadow(vec2 p, vec2 pos, float radius)
{
 vec2 dir = normalize(pos - p);
 float dl = length(p - pos);

 // fraction of light visible, starts at one radius (second half added in the end);
 float lf = radius \* dl;

 // distance traveled
 float dt = 0.01;

 for (int i = 0; i < 64; ++i)
 { 
 // distance to scene at current position
 float sd = sceneDist(p + dir \* dt);

 // early out when this ray is guaranteed to be full shadow
 if (sd < -radius) 
 return 0.0;

 // width of cone-overlap at light
 // 0 in center, so 50% overlap: add one radius outside of loop to get total coverage
 // should be '(sd / dt) \* dl', but '\*dl' outside of loop
 lf = min(lf, sd / dt);

 // move ahead
 dt += max(1.0, abs(sd));
 if (dt > dl) break;
 }

 // multiply by dl to get the real projected overlap (moved out of loop)
 // add one radius, before between -radius and + radius
 // normalize to 1 ( / 2\*radius)
 lf = clamp((lf\*dl + radius) / (2.0 \* radius), 0.0, 1.0);
 lf = smoothstep(0.0, 1.0, lf);
 return lf;
}

Step 8 of the project outline involves detecting when a row is filled and removing it from the game board.

To accomplish this, you can add a new method called `checkRows` to the `TetrisGame` class. This method will iterate over the rows of the game board and check if each row is filled. If a row is filled, it will remove it and move all the rows above it down. Here's the code for the `checkRows` method:
```java
private void checkRows() {
    int numRowsCleared = 0;
    for (int y = 0; y < GAME_BOARD_HEIGHT; y++) {
        boolean isRowFilled = true;
        for (int x = 0; x < GAME_BOARD_WIDTH; x++) {
            if (gameBoard[x][y] == null) {
                isRowFilled = false;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (isRowFilled) {
            // Remove row
            for (int x = 0; x < GAME_BOARD_WIDTH; x++) {
                for (int yy = y; yy > 0; yy--) {
                    gameBoard[x][yy] = gameBoard[x][yy - 1];
                }
                gameBoard[x][0] = null;
            }
            numRowsCleared++;
        }
    }
    if (numRowsCleared > 0) {
        score += SCORE_PER_ROW * numRowsCleared;
        display.update(gameBoard, currentTetromino, score);
    }
}
```
This code iterates over the rows of the game board using nested loops. For each row, it checks if every cell is filled by checking if it contains a non-null `TetrominoSquare` object. If the row is filled, it removes it by moving all the rows above it down by one cell.

After removing the rows, the method updates the score by adding `SCORE_PER_ROW * numRowsCleared` to it, where `SCORE_PER_ROW` is a constant value. Finally, it calls the `update` method of the display to update the game board and score.

You can call the `checkRows` method at the end of the `update` method to check for filled rows after each update. Here's the updated `update` method:
```java
private void update() {
    if (currentTetromino == null) {
        currentTetromino = Tetromino.getRandomTetromino();
        if (!canTetrominoMove(currentTetromino, 0, 0)) {
            display.showGameOverScreen();
            return;
        }
    }
    if (canTetrominoMove(currentTetromino, 0, 1)) {
        currentTetromino.move(0, 1);
    } else {
        // Add current Tetromino to game board
        addTetrominoToGameBoard(currentTetromino);
        checkRows();
        currentTetromino = null;
    }
    display.update(gameBoard, currentTetromino, score);
}
```
This code calls the `checkRows` method after adding the current Tetromino to the game board and before resetting the current Tetromino to `null`.

