You can create two variables to keep track of the scores, for example `playerScore` and `computerScore`, and update them every time a player wins a round. To store and remember every time that the player or computer has won, you can create two arrays, for example `playerWins` and `computerWins`, and push the card objects of the winning rounds to the corresponding array.

Here's an example of how you can modify the `deal()` function to implement these changes:
```javascript
let player1, player2;
let playerScore = 0;
let computerScore = 0;
const playerWins = [];
const computerWins = [];

function deal() {
    if (!player1 || !player2) {
        [player1, player2] = shuffleAndDealCards();
    }

    const card1 = player1.splice(Math.floor(Math.random() * player1.length), 1)[0];
    const card2 = player2.splice(Math.floor(Math.random() * player2.length), 1)[0];

    document.getElementById("card1").src = card1.image;
    document.getElementById("card2").src = card2.image;

    if (card1.value > card2.value) {
        playerScore++;
        playerWins.push(card1, card2);
    } else if (card1.value < card2.value) {
        computerScore++;
        computerWins.push(card1, card2);
    } else {
        playerWins.push(card1);
        computerWins.push(card2);
    }

    document.getElementById("player-score").textContent = `Player Score: ${playerScore}`;
    document.getElementById("computer-score").textContent = `Computer Score: ${computerScore}`;
}
```
In this example, the `playerScore` and `computerScore` variables are initialized to 0 at the beginning of the function, and the `playerWins` and `computerWins` arrays are initialized to empty arrays.

Every time a player wins a round, their corresponding score variable is incremented, and the card objects of the winning rounds are pushed to the corresponding array.

Finally, the updated scores are displayed on the page using the `textContent` property of the corresponding DOM elements.

